## v1.1.0 (2026-07-04)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1811 planning session — pipeline foundation layer
**Verification:** unverified (still a PLAN; no pytest/mypy/CI was run; no code executed)

### What changed
- Added a NEW real-world instance of the skill's exact subject: ProjectHephaestus issue
  #1811 planned to REMOVE the stale coverage-omit entry
  `hephaestus/automation/github_api.py` — the flat module was converted into a
  `github_api/` PACKAGE, so the `.py` path no longer exists on disk. Unlike the v1.0.0
  #1362 instance (where the edit was dropped as unnecessary), here the removal is
  load-bearing and correct.
- Encoded the durable NEW sub-lesson: **a frozen exact-set guard can have MORE THAN TWO
  co-update homes.** #1811 requires editing THREE synchronized homes, not two:
  1. `pyproject.toml` `[tool.coverage.run].omit` (the actual list),
  2. `tests/unit/validation/test_omit_allowlist.py` `expected_modules` (the frozen
     hard-coded copy — same guard as #1362),
  3. `tests/integration/test_orchestration_smoke.py` — a PROSE COUNT in the module
     DOCSTRING ("17 automation modules" → 16; "10 modules lack main()" → 9) plus an
     enumeration line naming `github_api`. This is NOT a Python set; the smoke test
     derives the module list from `pyproject.toml` at runtime, so the docstring count is
     documentation that drifts SILENTLY and is asserted only indirectly. A "N modules"
     comment IS a co-update site.
- Encoded "re-derive the ground state, don't trust the description": the plan confirmed
  via `ls` that `hephaestus/automation/github_api.py` is genuinely GONE (replaced by the
  `github_api/` package dir) BEFORE removing its omit entry. A frozen-list entry can ROT
  when its underlying file is renamed/packaged; removing a dead entry is safe ONLY after a
  filesystem check proves the path no longer exists. This is the "prove the edit is safe"
  branch of the skill, grounded in `ls` rather than sibling-test precedent.
- Overview: bumped Date to 2026-07-04; rewrote Objective and Outcome to cover both the
  #1362 (drop-the-edit) and #1811 (three-home co-update of a stale entry) instances.
- Added an "### New instance (2026-07-04): #1811" subsection under Overview describing the
  three homes and the two durable additions (prose-count home; re-derive ground state).
- When to Use: added two bullets (removing a stale entry whose file was packaged away;
  a list mirrored by a human-readable COUNT no assertion pins).
- Quick Reference: added greps for the second-order prose count and for the entry itself
  tree-wide, plus an `ls` ground-state check; changed "co-update BOTH" to "co-update ALL
  homes".
- Detailed Steps: rewrote step 2 to grep EVERY home (entry tree-wide, frozen guard, prose
  count); added a new step 3 (re-derive ground state via `ls` before removing a stale
  entry); renumbered the rest to 4-6; step 6 now says to re-grep by content because cited
  line numbers drift.
- Failed Attempts: added three #1811 rows (assume exactly two homes; trust a stale entry
  points at a real file; anchor edits to drifting line numbers).
- Results & Parameters: added the three-home breakdown (with point-in-time line numbers
