### Why
This session produced a fresh real-world instance of the skill's exact subject that adds
two durable lessons the v1.0.0 skill did not capture: (1) a frozen list's invariant can
live in MORE THAN TWO homes, and one of them can be a human-readable prose/docstring count
that no assertion pins yet still drifts silently — so "grep for every home" must include
prose counts, not just the `*_frozen` assertion; and (2) a frozen-list entry can go STALE
when its underlying file is renamed/packaged, making removal load-bearing and safe only
after a filesystem `ls` re-derives the ground state. Both are reusable planning lessons,
not specific to the omit list, so they are folded into the skill (MINOR bump: new instance
plus a new sub-lesson, no core rewrite). The framing stays a "Proposed Workflow"/warning
and `verification: unverified` because #1811 is a PLAN — no code was executed, no tests or
CI ran.

